  "summary": "autotel-devtools 6.2.0: pattern matches in bundled CLI need human review",
  "details": "Bundled distribution files (dist/cli.cjs, dist/cli.js, dist/index.cjs, dist/index.js, dist/server/index.cjs, dist/server/index.js, dist/widget.global.js) contain keyword co-occurrences flagged by pattern rules: Buffer.from(..., 'base64') decoding alongside.toString() calls, and 'curl'/'ping'/'POST' tokens within minified bundles. None of these patterns, in isolation, are sufficient to attribute malicious intent — base64 decoding is common in legitimate tooling (JWT handling, asset embedding, source maps) and 'curl'/'ping'/'POST' string literals can appear in shell helpers, diagnostics, or HTTP libraries. No attacker-controlled domain, hardcoded C2, credential path read, env-var scrape, lifecycle hook abuse, or install-time fetch-and-execute pattern is established by the available evidence. Routing to human review so a reviewer can de-minify the flagged spans and confirm whether the base64 decode and outbound request paths are part of the package's documented devtools/widget functionality or something more concerning.",
